01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>89000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Wellcome Trust Seed Grant</gtr:description><gtr:end>2017-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Wellcome Trust</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>C37F3E30-0195-4300-A6B4-7EDBB332E35F</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>59103d5d866bf4.36442886</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-07-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have now identified a number of key insights into how peer review evaluators approach the assessment of impact. These were tested in the post evaluation interviews, and we found that very little evaluation was based on traditional peer review debate and discussion, as is the case for scientific impact. Instead we found that the evaluators were influenced by the HEFCE guidelines, and other external influences (such as the calibration exercise). This does not bode well for the future of societal impact evaluation using peer review, as it is unlikely that peer review committees will be adequately placed to address the question of societal impact evaluation alone.

We have also developed some key hypotheses regarding the potential biases, as well as the use of particular indicators to assess research impact.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>At this stage of the research project, it is unclear how these findings will be taken forward. The next part of the research project (to be undertaken 2016) will provide further, more valid insights that will be put into us by funding agencies, research organisations, research evaluators, and researchers themselves.

